1
00:00:01,190 --> 00:00:03,360
Let's see how we can use

2
00:00:03,360 --> 00:00:05,460
reinforcement
learning to control

3
00:00:05,460 --> 00:00:07,365
the Lunar Lander or

4
00:00:07,365 --> 00:00:09,750
for other reinforcement
learning problems.

5
00:00:09,750 --> 00:00:12,180
The key idea is that we're going

6
00:00:12,180 --> 00:00:14,460
to train a neural network to

7
00:00:14,460 --> 00:00:16,620
compute or to approximate

8
00:00:16,620 --> 00:00:19,900
the state action value
function Q of s,

9
00:00:19,900 --> 00:00:23,280
a and that in turn will
let us pick good actions.

10
00:00:23,280 --> 00:00:24,825
Let's see how it works.

11
00:00:24,825 --> 00:00:27,630
The heart of the learning
algorithm is we're going to

12
00:00:27,630 --> 00:00:30,315
train a neural
network that inputs

13
00:00:30,315 --> 00:00:33,930
the current state and
the current action and

14
00:00:33,930 --> 00:00:38,355
computes or
approximates Q of s, a.

15
00:00:38,355 --> 00:00:41,775
In particular, for
the Lunar Lander,

16
00:00:41,775 --> 00:00:44,295
we're going to take
the state s and

17
00:00:44,295 --> 00:00:47,105
any action a and
put them together.

18
00:00:47,105 --> 00:00:49,490
Concretely, the state was

19
00:00:49,490 --> 00:00:52,930
that list of eight numbers
that we saw previously,

20
00:00:52,930 --> 00:00:56,190
so you have xy, x dot,

21
00:00:56,190 --> 00:00:59,445
y dot, Theta, Theta dot,

22
00:00:59,445 --> 00:01:02,355
and then LR for where
the legs are grounded,

23
00:01:02,355 --> 00:01:04,400
so that's a list
of eight numbers

24
00:01:04,400 --> 00:01:05,845
that describe the state.

25
00:01:05,845 --> 00:01:09,580
Then finally, we have four
possible actions: nothing,

26
00:01:09,580 --> 00:01:12,530
left, main, a main
engine, and right.

27
00:01:12,530 --> 00:01:15,305
We can encode any of
those four actions

28
00:01:15,305 --> 00:01:18,485
using a one-hot feature vector.

29
00:01:18,485 --> 00:01:21,545
If action were the first action,

30
00:01:21,545 --> 00:01:24,875
we may encode it using 1, 0, 0,

31
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:26,780
0 or if it was

32
00:01:26,780 --> 00:01:29,570
the second action to
find the left cluster,

33
00:01:29,570 --> 00:01:33,585
we may encode it as 0, 1, 0, 0.

34
00:01:33,585 --> 00:01:36,425
This list of 12 numbers,

35
00:01:36,425 --> 00:01:39,500
eight numbers for the state
and then four numbers,

36
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:41,585
a one-hot encoding of the action

37
00:01:41,585 --> 00:01:44,750
is the inputs we'll have
to the neural network,

38
00:01:44,750 --> 00:01:47,295
and I'm going to call this X.

39
00:01:47,295 --> 00:01:49,700
We'll then take these
12 numbers and feed

40
00:01:49,700 --> 00:01:52,685
them to a neural
network with say,

41
00:01:52,685 --> 00:01:55,100
64 units in the
first hidden layer,

42
00:01:55,100 --> 00:01:57,380
64 units in the
second hidden layer,

43
00:01:57,380 --> 00:02:00,700
and then a single output
in the output layer.

44
00:02:00,700 --> 00:02:05,720
The job of the neural network
is the output Q of s, a.

45
00:02:05,720 --> 00:02:08,000
The state action-value
function for

46
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,575
the Lunar Lander given
the input s and a.

47
00:02:11,575 --> 00:02:13,370
Because we'll be using

48
00:02:13,370 --> 00:02:16,190
neural network training
algorithms in a little bit,

49
00:02:16,190 --> 00:02:19,570
I'm also going to refer
to this value Q of s,

50
00:02:19,570 --> 00:02:22,715
a as the target value Y

51
00:02:22,715 --> 00:02:25,445
that were training the neural
network to approximate.

52
00:02:25,445 --> 00:02:27,200
Notice that I did say

53
00:02:27,200 --> 00:02:28,880
reinforcement
learning is different

54
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:30,400
from supervised learning,

55
00:02:30,400 --> 00:02:32,720
but what we're
going to do is not

56
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:35,345
input a state and have
it output an action.

57
00:02:35,345 --> 00:02:37,250
What we're going to do is input

58
00:02:37,250 --> 00:02:41,390
a state action pair and have
it try to output Q of s,

59
00:02:41,390 --> 00:02:44,780
a, and using a neural
network inside

60
00:02:44,780 --> 00:02:46,250
the reinforcement
learning algorithm this

61
00:02:46,250 --> 00:02:48,635
way will turn out to
work pretty well.

62
00:02:48,635 --> 00:02:50,000
We'll see the details in

63
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:51,800
a little bit so don't

64
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:54,205
worry about it if it
doesn't make sense yet.

65
00:02:54,205 --> 00:02:56,660
But if you can train
a neural network

66
00:02:56,660 --> 00:02:59,630
with appropriate choices
of parameters in

67
00:02:59,630 --> 00:03:02,090
the hidden layers and
in the upper layer

68
00:03:02,090 --> 00:03:04,970
to give you a good
estimates of Q of s,

69
00:03:04,970 --> 00:03:07,490
a, then whenever you're

70
00:03:07,490 --> 00:03:10,520
Lunar Lander is in some state s,

71
00:03:10,520 --> 00:03:12,830
you can then use the
neural network to

72
00:03:12,830 --> 00:03:15,500
compute Q of s, a.

73
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:16,955
For all four actions,

74
00:03:16,955 --> 00:03:19,280
you can compute Q of s, nothing,

75
00:03:19,280 --> 00:03:20,570
Q of s, left, Q of s,

76
00:03:20,570 --> 00:03:22,195
main, Q of s, right,

77
00:03:22,195 --> 00:03:23,615
and then finally,

78
00:03:23,615 --> 00:03:26,690
whichever of these has
the highest value,

79
00:03:26,690 --> 00:03:29,980
you pick the
corresponding action a.

80
00:03:29,980 --> 00:03:33,860
For example, if out of
these four values, Q of s,

81
00:03:33,860 --> 00:03:36,950
main is largest, then you would

82
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:38,270
decide to go and fire

83
00:03:38,270 --> 00:03:41,080
the main engine of
the Lunar Lander.

84
00:03:41,080 --> 00:03:44,465
The question becomes,
how do you train

85
00:03:44,465 --> 00:03:48,140
a neural network to
output Q of s, a?

86
00:03:48,140 --> 00:03:50,450
It turns out the
approach will be to use

87
00:03:50,450 --> 00:03:52,520
Bellman's equations to create

88
00:03:52,520 --> 00:03:55,129
a training set with
lots of examples,

89
00:03:55,129 --> 00:03:56,925
x and y,

90
00:03:56,925 --> 00:03:58,955
and then we'll use
supervised learning

91
00:03:58,955 --> 00:04:00,335
exactly as you learned

92
00:04:00,335 --> 00:04:02,090
in the second course

93
00:04:02,090 --> 00:04:04,160
when we talked about
neural networks.

94
00:04:04,160 --> 00:04:06,950
To learn using
supervised learning,

95
00:04:06,950 --> 00:04:08,840
a mapping from x to y,

96
00:04:08,840 --> 00:04:09,950
that is a mapping from

97
00:04:09,950 --> 00:04:15,560
the state action pair to
this target value Q of s, a.

98
00:04:15,560 --> 00:04:19,610
But how do you get the
training set with values for

99
00:04:19,610 --> 00:04:21,770
x and y that you can then

100
00:04:21,770 --> 00:04:24,880
train a neural network
on? Let's take a look.

101
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:27,660
Here's the Bellman
equation, Q of s,

102
00:04:27,660 --> 00:04:29,940
a equals R of s plus Gamma,

103
00:04:29,940 --> 00:04:33,060
max of a prime, Q of
s prime, a prime.

104
00:04:33,060 --> 00:04:37,200
The right-hand side is
what you want Q of s,

105
00:04:37,200 --> 00:04:38,465
a to be equal to,

106
00:04:38,465 --> 00:04:40,940
so I'm going to
call this value on

107
00:04:40,940 --> 00:04:44,180
the right-hand side
y and the input

108
00:04:44,180 --> 00:04:46,790
to the neural network
is a state and

109
00:04:46,790 --> 00:04:50,265
an action so I'm
going to call that x.

110
00:04:50,265 --> 00:04:53,750
The job of the neural
network is to input x,

111
00:04:53,750 --> 00:04:55,685
that is input the
state action pair,

112
00:04:55,685 --> 00:04:57,740
and try to accurately

113
00:04:57,740 --> 00:05:01,060
predict what will be
the value on the right.

114
00:05:01,060 --> 00:05:03,890
In supervised learning,
we were training

115
00:05:03,890 --> 00:05:07,140
a neural network to
learn a function f,

116
00:05:07,140 --> 00:05:09,660
which depends on a
bunch of parameters,

117
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:11,300
W and B, the parameters

118
00:05:11,300 --> 00:05:13,280
of the various layers
of the neural network

119
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:19,175
and it was the job of the
neural network to input x.

120
00:05:19,175 --> 00:05:25,220
Hopefully I'll put something
close to the target value y.

121
00:05:25,220 --> 00:05:27,530
The question is, how can we come

122
00:05:27,530 --> 00:05:29,390
up with a training set with

123
00:05:29,390 --> 00:05:35,900
values x and y for a new
network to learn from.

124
00:05:35,900 --> 00:05:38,600
Here's what we're going
to do. We're going to use

125
00:05:38,600 --> 00:05:40,250
the lunar lander and

126
00:05:40,250 --> 00:05:42,770
just try taking
different actions in it.

127
00:05:42,770 --> 00:05:45,110
If we don't have a
good policy yet,

128
00:05:45,110 --> 00:05:46,865
we'll take actions randomly,

129
00:05:46,865 --> 00:05:49,310
further, left fasser, further,

130
00:05:49,310 --> 00:05:50,450
right fasser further,

131
00:05:50,450 --> 00:05:52,880
main engine, do nothing.

132
00:05:52,880 --> 00:05:54,800
By just trying out

133
00:05:54,800 --> 00:05:58,490
different things in the
lunar lander simulator

134
00:05:58,490 --> 00:06:01,490
we'll observe a lot
of examples of when

135
00:06:01,490 --> 00:06:04,385
we're in some state and
we took some action,

136
00:06:04,385 --> 00:06:07,745
may be a good action, maybe a
terrible action either way.

137
00:06:07,745 --> 00:06:12,665
Then we got some reward R of
s for being in that state,

138
00:06:12,665 --> 00:06:14,780
and as a result of our action,

139
00:06:14,780 --> 00:06:17,750
we got to some new state, S'.

140
00:06:17,750 --> 00:06:21,320
As you take different
actions in the lunar lander,

141
00:06:21,320 --> 00:06:22,760
you see this S,

142
00:06:22,760 --> 00:06:24,620
a, R of s, S',

143
00:06:24,620 --> 00:06:27,890
and we call them tuples in
Python code many times.

144
00:06:27,890 --> 00:06:31,010
For example, maybe one time
you're in some state S

145
00:06:31,010 --> 00:06:34,905
and just to give this an
index and we call this S^1,

146
00:06:34,905 --> 00:06:37,850
and you happen to
take some action a^1,

147
00:06:37,850 --> 00:06:39,140
this could be nothing left,

148
00:06:39,140 --> 00:06:40,865
main thrusts there or right.

149
00:06:40,865 --> 00:06:44,225
As a result of which
you've got some reward,

150
00:06:44,225 --> 00:06:48,395
and you want up at
some state S^'1.

151
00:06:48,395 --> 00:06:51,470
Maybe at different times
you're in some other state S2,

152
00:06:51,470 --> 00:06:53,480
you took some other action,

153
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:55,280
could be good action,
could be bad action,

154
00:06:55,280 --> 00:06:56,810
could be any of
the four actions,

155
00:06:56,810 --> 00:06:59,060
and you got the reward,

156
00:06:59,060 --> 00:07:04,175
and then you want up with S
'2 and so on multiple times.

157
00:07:04,175 --> 00:07:06,320
Maybe you've done this 10,000

158
00:07:06,320 --> 00:07:08,465
times or even more
than 10,000 times,

159
00:07:08,465 --> 00:07:13,250
so you would have to save
the way with not just S^1,

160
00:07:13,250 --> 00:07:16,505
a^1 and so on, but up
to S^10,000, a^10,000.

161
00:07:16,505 --> 00:07:22,610
It turns out that each
of these tuples will

162
00:07:22,610 --> 00:07:28,865
be enough to create a single
training example, x^1, y^1.

163
00:07:28,865 --> 00:07:31,055
In particular, here's
how you do it.

164
00:07:31,055 --> 00:07:34,595
There are four elements
in this first tuple.

165
00:07:34,595 --> 00:07:38,630
The first two will be
used to compute x^1,

166
00:07:38,630 --> 00:07:42,470
and the second two would
be used to compute y^1.

167
00:07:42,470 --> 00:07:46,670
In particular, x^1
is just going to be

168
00:07:46,670 --> 00:07:51,350
S^1, a^1 put together.

169
00:07:51,350 --> 00:07:53,735
S^1 would be eight numbers,

170
00:07:53,735 --> 00:07:55,850
the state of the lunar lander,

171
00:07:55,850 --> 00:07:57,470
a^1 would be four numbers,

172
00:07:57,470 --> 00:08:01,445
the one-hot encoding of whatever
action this was and y^1

173
00:08:01,445 --> 00:08:02,720
would be computed using

174
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:05,750
the right-hand side of
the Bellman equation.

175
00:08:05,750 --> 00:08:08,555
In particular, the
Bellman equation says,

176
00:08:08,555 --> 00:08:11,150
when you input S^1,

177
00:08:11,150 --> 00:08:13,880
a^1, you want Q of S^1,

178
00:08:13,880 --> 00:08:16,175
a^1 to be this right hand side,

179
00:08:16,175 --> 00:08:21,050
to be equal to R
of S^1 plus Gamma

180
00:08:21,050 --> 00:08:28,280
max over a' of Q
of S^1'a' prime.

181
00:08:28,280 --> 00:08:31,400
Notice that these two
elements of the tuple

182
00:08:31,400 --> 00:08:34,790
on the right give you enough
information to compute this.

183
00:08:34,790 --> 00:08:37,760
You know what is R of S^1?

184
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:39,935
That's the reward you've
saved the way here.

185
00:08:39,935 --> 00:08:41,990
Plus the discount factor gamma

186
00:08:41,990 --> 00:08:44,300
times max over all actions,

187
00:08:44,300 --> 00:08:47,165
a' of Q of S'^1,

188
00:08:47,165 --> 00:08:49,970
that's a state you got
to in this example,

189
00:08:49,970 --> 00:08:53,135
and then take the maximum over
all possible actions, a'.

190
00:08:53,135 --> 00:08:56,310
I'm going to call this y^1.

191
00:08:56,860 --> 00:08:59,060
When you compute this,

192
00:08:59,060 --> 00:09:04,145
this will be some
number like 12.5 or 17,

193
00:09:04,145 --> 00:09:06,380
or 0.5 or some other number.

194
00:09:06,380 --> 00:09:10,145
We'll save that
number here as y^1,

195
00:09:10,145 --> 00:09:12,710
so that this pair x^1,

196
00:09:12,710 --> 00:09:15,560
y^1 becomes the first
training example

197
00:09:15,560 --> 00:09:17,705
in this low dataset
we're computing.

198
00:09:17,705 --> 00:09:20,195
Now, you may be wondering,

199
00:09:20,195 --> 00:09:22,775
where does Q of S',

200
00:09:22,775 --> 00:09:27,140
a' or Q of S'^1, a' come from.

201
00:09:27,140 --> 00:09:31,025
Well, initially we don't
know what is the Q function.

202
00:09:31,025 --> 00:09:32,810
But it turns out that when you

203
00:09:32,810 --> 00:09:34,565
don't know what is
the Q function,

204
00:09:34,565 --> 00:09:37,100
you can start off with taking
a totally random guess.

205
00:09:37,100 --> 00:09:38,720
What is the Q function?

206
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:40,820
We'll see on the
next slide that the

207
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:43,040
[inaudible] will
work nonetheless.

208
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:47,810
But in every step Q here is
just going to be some guess.

209
00:09:47,810 --> 00:09:49,430
They'll get better
over time it turns

210
00:09:49,430 --> 00:09:52,155
out of what is the
actual Q function.

211
00:09:52,155 --> 00:09:53,920
Let's look at the
second example.

212
00:09:53,920 --> 00:09:56,515
If you had a second experience

213
00:09:56,515 --> 00:09:58,825
where you are in state
S^2 to got to a^2,

214
00:09:58,825 --> 00:10:01,195
got that reward and
then got to that state.

215
00:10:01,195 --> 00:10:02,560
Then we would create

216
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:05,305
a second training
example in this dataset,

217
00:10:05,305 --> 00:10:10,500
x^2, where the input
is now S^2, a^2,

218
00:10:10,500 --> 00:10:14,150
so the first two elements go
to computing the input x,

219
00:10:14,150 --> 00:10:20,440
and then y^2 will be
equal to R of s^2 plus

220
00:10:20,440 --> 00:10:27,755
gamma max of a' Q of S' to a',

221
00:10:27,755 --> 00:10:30,815
and whatever this
number is, y^2.

222
00:10:30,815 --> 00:10:32,795
We put this over here

223
00:10:32,795 --> 00:10:35,075
in our small but
growing training set,

224
00:10:35,075 --> 00:10:37,160
and so on and so forth,

225
00:10:37,160 --> 00:10:39,950
until maybe you end up with

226
00:10:39,950 --> 00:10:46,280
10,000 training examples
with these x, y pairs.

227
00:10:46,280 --> 00:10:48,920
What we'll see
later is that we'll

228
00:10:48,920 --> 00:10:51,845
actually take this
training set where the

229
00:10:51,845 --> 00:10:53,750
x's are inputs with

230
00:10:53,750 --> 00:10:57,815
12 features and the
y's are just numbers.

231
00:10:57,815 --> 00:11:00,845
We'll train a new
network with, say,

232
00:11:00,845 --> 00:11:04,220
the mean squared
error loss to try to

233
00:11:04,220 --> 00:11:08,660
predict y as a function
of the input x.

234
00:11:08,660 --> 00:11:10,520
What I describe here is

235
00:11:10,520 --> 00:11:13,955
just one piece of the
learning algorithm we'll use.

236
00:11:13,955 --> 00:11:16,310
Let's put it all together
on the next slide and see

237
00:11:16,310 --> 00:11:19,370
how it all comes together
into a single algorithm.

238
00:11:19,370 --> 00:11:21,260
Let's take a look at what

239
00:11:21,260 --> 00:11:25,265
a full algorithm for learning
the Q-function is like.

240
00:11:25,265 --> 00:11:28,685
First, we're going to take
our neural network and

241
00:11:28,685 --> 00:11:30,500
initialize all the parameters

242
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:32,465
of the neural network randomly.

243
00:11:32,465 --> 00:11:34,625
Initially we have no idea,

244
00:11:34,625 --> 00:11:36,065
whether it's a Q function,

245
00:11:36,065 --> 00:11:38,810
let's just pick totally
random values of the widths.

246
00:11:38,810 --> 00:11:41,510
We'll pretend that
this neural network is

247
00:11:41,510 --> 00:11:44,610
our initial random guess
for the Q-function.

248
00:11:44,610 --> 00:11:46,855
This is a little bit
like when you are

249
00:11:46,855 --> 00:11:49,315
training linear
regression and you

250
00:11:49,315 --> 00:11:51,735
initialize all the
parameters randomly

251
00:11:51,735 --> 00:11:54,830
and then use gradient descent
to improve the parameters.

252
00:11:54,830 --> 00:11:57,155
Initializing it randomly
for now is fine.

253
00:11:57,155 --> 00:11:59,960
What's important is
whether the algorithm can

